    • Method Detail

      • execute

        public void execute(CommandContext context)
        Contrary to other commands that blindly process each file in a directory, this command first looks for a specific file, as defined by the forestFilename attribute. If that file is found, then its contents are used as the payload for creating forests. Otherwise, if the forestPayload attribute has been set, then its contents are used as the payload. If neither is true, then no forests are created.

      • createForests

        protected void createForests(java.lang.String originalPayload,
                             CommandContext context)
        This command manages a couple of its own tokens, as it's expected that the host and forest name should be dynamically generated based on what hosts exist and how many forests should be created on each host.
